<a name="List-Processing-1"></a>
<h2 class="chapter">1 List Processing</h2>

<p>To the untutored eye, Lisp is a strange programming language.  In Lisp
code there are parentheses everywhere.  Some people even claim that
the name stands for &ldquo;Lots of Isolated Silly Parentheses&rdquo;.  But the
claim is unwarranted.  Lisp stands for LISt Processing, and the
programming language handles <em>lists</em> (and lists of lists) by
putting them between parentheses.  The parentheses mark the boundaries
of the list.  Sometimes a list is preceded by an apostrophe &lsquo;<samp>'</samp>&rsquo;,
called a <em>single-quote</em> in Lisp.<a name="DOCF1" href="#FOOT1"><sup>1</sup></a>  Lists are the basis
of Lisp.
</p>
