<a name="Cutting-and-Storing-Text"></a>
<h2 class="chapter">8 Cutting and Storing Text</h2>
<a name="index-Cutting-and-storing-text"></a>
<a name="index-Storing-and-cutting-text"></a>
<a name="index-Killing-text"></a>
<a name="index-Clipping-text"></a>
<a name="index-Erasing-text"></a>
<a name="index-Deleting-text"></a>

<p>Whenever you cut or clip text out of a buffer with a <em>kill</em> command in
GNU Emacs, it is stored in a list and you can bring it back with a
<em>yank</em> command.
</p>
<p>(The use of the word &ldquo;kill&rdquo; in Emacs for processes which specifically
<em>do not</em> destroy the values of the entities is an unfortunate
historical accident.  A much more appropriate word would be &ldquo;clip&rdquo; since
that is what the kill commands do; they clip text out of a buffer and
put it into storage from which it can be brought back.  I have often
been tempted to replace globally all occurrences of &ldquo;kill&rdquo; in the Emacs
sources with &ldquo;clip&rdquo; and all occurrences of &ldquo;killed&rdquo; with &ldquo;clipped&rdquo;.)
</p>
