<a name="while"></a>
<div class="header">
<p>
Next: <a href="#dolist-dotimes" accesskey="n" rel="next">dolist dotimes</a>, Up: <a href="#Loops-_0026-Recursion" accesskey="u" rel="up">Loops &amp; Recursion</a> &nbsp; [<a href="#SEC_Contents" title="Table of contents" rel="contents">Contents</a>][<a href="#Index" title="Index" rel="index">Index</a>]</p>
</div>
<a name="while-1"></a>
<h3 class="section">11.1 <code>while</code></h3>
<a name="index-Loops"></a>
<a name="index-while"></a>

<p>The <code>while</code> special form tests whether the value returned by
evaluating its first argument is true or false.  This is similar to what
the Lisp interpreter does with an <code>if</code>; what the interpreter does
next, however, is different.
</p>
<p>In a <code>while</code> expression, if the value returned by evaluating the
first argument is false, the Lisp interpreter skips the rest of the
expression (the <em>body</em> of the expression) and does not evaluate it.
However, if the value is true, the Lisp interpreter evaluates the body
of the expression and then again tests whether the first argument to
<code>while</code> is true or false.  If the value returned by evaluating the
first argument is again true, the Lisp interpreter again evaluates the
body of the expression.
</p>
<p>The template for a <code>while</code> expression looks like this:
</p>
<div class="smallexample">
<pre class="smallexample">(while <var>true-or-false-test</var>
  <var>body</var>&hellip;)
</pre></div>

<table class="menu" border="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr><td align="left" valign="top">&bull; <a href="#Looping-with-while" accesskey="1">Looping with while</a>:</td><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;</td><td align="left" valign="top">Repeat so long as test returns true.
</td></tr>
<tr><td align="left" valign="top">&bull; <a href="#Loop-Example" accesskey="2">Loop Example</a>:</td><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;</td><td align="left" valign="top">A <code>while</code> loop that uses a list.
</td></tr>
