<a name="forward_002dsentence-1"></a>
<h3 class="section">12.3 <code>forward-sentence</code></h3>
<a name="index-forward_002dsentence"></a>

<p>The command to move the cursor forward a sentence is a straightforward
illustration of how to use regular expression searches in Emacs Lisp.
Indeed, the function looks longer and more complicated than it is; this
is because the function is designed to go backwards as well as forwards;
and, optionally, over more than one sentence.  The function is usually
bound to the key command <kbd>M-e</kbd>.
</p>
<table class="menu" border="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr><td align="left" valign="top">&bull; <a href="#Complete-forward_002dsentence" accesskey="1">Complete forward-sentence</a>:</td><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;</td><td align="left" valign="top">
</td></tr>
<tr><td align="left" valign="top">&bull; <a href="#fwd_002dsentence-while-loops" accesskey="2">fwd-sentence while loops</a>:</td><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;</td><td align="left" valign="top">Two <code>while</code> loops.
</td></tr>
